content.description:
The first sport route in

American Fork Canyon

.

Pockets to slopers on solid, dark limestone.
content.location: The third line from the right on the wall to the left of the cave mouth.

content.description: A mysterious route that starts in the back of the cave.
content.location: Starts on top of a choss tower to the left of True Lies. It follow the prow/arete feature into the top of the cave and ends at the Helix anchor.

content.description:
Simian's little brother.  Still not to be trifled with.

Some rough slab climbing to a strange bulge above.  Shares anchors with simian.
content.protection: Long; 10+ draws to chain anchors, I'd bring 13-14 draws.  Shares anchors with Simian.
content.location: Between Black Magic and Simian, right near the left mouth of the cave.

content.description: Starts at the very back of the cave, near a good size ledge.  Near horizontal climbing to a set of anchors near the end of Helix
content.protection: ~5 bolts to chains.  Definitely will require cleaning on top rope, too steep to clean via lowering.
content.location: Very back-center of the cave, climbing straight out towards the mouth.

content.description:
A thin, perplexing start leads to some tenuous moves trending up and left to the third bolt.

From the third bolt head more-or-less straight up through an overhanging section with some good holds, and some-not-so-good holds. Getting up and past the fourth bolt is probably the crux; it requires some body-positioning trickery, and a bit of faith that holds are coming (it feels a wee bit exposed).

After the last bolt is a concentration-inducing runout to the chains.
content.location:
Found on the downhill (left) side of the wall to the left of the

Black Magic

cave.

Just after starting up the hill on the wooden steps there is a left-facing dihedral with bolts along its left side, and at the top of the dihedral a bolt on the right side. This is not the route.

The route is the next bolt line left. The first two bolts trend slightly left; the third bolt, above a shallow ramp is farther left.

Note that this line shares the first three bolts with an .11c to the left.

content.description: Others may disagree, but I think this route is classic. The slab start is awesome, even though you're pissed every time you have to climb it (at least I was). It's hard. After the slab, you get a decent rest before climbing through a pretty difficult boulder problem out the steepest part of the roof. Another little rest helps you recover before finishing up on insecure holds. Brilliant. This is the one route that haunts me for not redpointing before moving away....
content.location: This route is located to the left of The Helix, or two routes right of Black Magic.

content.description:
This route starts back downhill (East) of the Cave proper.  I believe it is the farthest left route on the wall...though things have become pretty gridded out (sigh) in this section of the cliff.Pass a bolt or two and make a cool span into a left facing corner under a roof, then make a difficult move to establish yourself above the roof.  Good and restful pockets leads to a hard finish.  Bouldery and on good, black rock, this route climbs like it belongs at the Hideaway...and probably is a touch soft for the grade, which is rare for any of Jeff's route.

A do not miss route for AF.
Shares a start with Problem Child.  Climb the first four bolts, then cut right and head to the anchors of Distraction.
content.protection: ~7ish bolts to chain anchors?  Bring 10 draws, you'll be good.
content.location: Shares a stat with Problem Child on the far left side of the main cave, at the bottom of a steep dirt hill.

content.description: starts left of helix on the vertical slab. Technical climbing over a tricky buldge (1st crux). Stand up, get a shake, then start the steep climbing up the flake on helix. Once at the top of the flake break right clipping two more bolts before the final crux guarding the chains.
content.location: Starts 15 feet to the left of helix.

content.description: Start on Orogeny and climb through the crux of Orogeny, at the headwall (6th bolt) split left and climb a really cool face with slightly harder moves than the headwall for Orogeny. This version adds a slightly harder and funner finish to Orogeny! The book calls this line a project, so I'm not sure who the FA is.
content.location: Starts on Orogeny, splits left at 6th bolt

content.description: Overhanging climbing leads to good stone above, one of the better routes on the wall.
content.location: Start on the right side of the cave. Its the second to last route. Climb up choss to first bolt then climb through roof/dihedral straight up and a little to the right...

content.description:
Not sure who put this up; rumoured to be called "Needles and Pins" Like many early AF routes this one's still cleaning up. Should be 11A when it does. Can feel much harder if you don't find the sequence (or clean holds). Take a brush....

Starts off with some stemming in a corner, which leads to a fun crux with some descent exposure. Good rest after the crux, then follows a crack to the chains.
content.location:
This is the right-most bolt line on the wall to the right of the cave.

A few feet right of

Orogeny

.

content.description:
Pumpy pulls through the roof lead to continual nontrivial travel above the lip of the cave. Purposely primal pulls lead to at a mid-crux and do not count the chicken until it is hatched. A final redpoint move may be in order. If this is 12c then it is SOLID for the grade. Feel free to uprate.

content.protection:
14 bolts

Descent: 3 bolt chain anchor. This is the highest anchor that can be seen about 12' left and 15' above the Orogony anchor. Looks like the other 2 linkups end here. 60m rope!
content.location: There are now a total of 4 routes that begin on Orogeny. This is outside the cave on the right side. Not sure about other 2 but this takes the leftmost new bolt line through the steepest part of the roof after the shared start for 3 or 4 bolts.

content.description:
Excellent quality rock with some exciting movement.

A slightly balancy start with big holds leads to a slight ledge. After the ledge comes a tricky dihedral that requires stemming, liebacking, and perseverance. Don't forget to try a finger lock.

The top of the dihedral is a bit strenuous; shortly after, however, comes a respite. After the break, start up a slabby bit on rounded footholds. Either go a little and surmount a bit of a roof, or stay right for a few tenuous, balancy moves.

Continue up and right a bit and cruise to the anchors.
content.location:
Found on the downhill (left) side of the wall to the left of the

Black Magic

cave.

Just after starting up the hill on the wooden steps there is a left-facing dihedral with bolts along its left side, and at the top of the dihedral a bolt on the right side. This is the route.

content.description: Start on Helix. After the 6th bolt break left, into some upside down climbing through some pods. Pull out the the lip of the cave and finish up a tricky, exposed slab.
Start on Helix. At the top of the flake break right and finish on Ouija.
Start on Ouija for 3 bolts. Finish on Helix.

If I were to list off a handful of the top middle 5.12 sport routes I've ever done, the list would probably start out something like this:- Rifle's "Pretty Hate Machine"- Cal Dome's "Ginsu"- VRG's "Mentor"- Cave Rock's "Fire in the Hole"- AF's "Helix"

Strong enough endorsement?

Anyway, if you find the Black Magic cave, you can't miss Helix.It starts on the left side of the cave and spirals up into a hole.Great fun!

Starts just to the right of helix. A few bolts up a sequential slab get you to the steep stuff. Power into some undercling pockets. Grab some awesome tufas. Get creative with the crux finish. Oh and don't be scared of a little bat guano.
content.location: Starts just to the right of Helix

content.description: Same start as Stay On The Porch; at the third bolt head left, and climb a few bolts before rejoining anchors with Stay On The Porch.  Shares anchors with that route.
content.protection: draws to chain anchors, ~10 draws will suffice.
content.location: Same start as Stay on the Porch, on the left side of the cave near the bottom of the steep dirt trail to the main cave.

content.description: Grab your hand jammies and helmet! Not since "Demon Wizard Bat" has there been such a futuristic linkup of American Fork choss. Probably the easiest way to climb the entirety of The Black Magic Cave, this hodgepodge of a climb starts on True Lies (12d) then climbs Helix (12-) backwards and downward toward the lip of the cave before finishing on Hexed (13a). While the route doesn’t seem to have any stopper moves, the redpoint crux seems to be the long sequence linking into and surmounting the lip with the pump. Be aware this route requires long slings, some runouts on easier terrain and the use of a spooky chalk stone. Not for everyone, but quite a fun challenge for the right rock weirdo. Make sure to brush up on your crack skills and cave tricks for this silly circus route.
content.location: Probably the easiest way to climb the entirety of the cave, this hodgepodge starts on "True Lies" (12d) then climbs "Helix" (12-) backwards and downward toward the lip of the cave before finishing on "Hexed" (13a).
